Assuming the XML document is a flat file on your server, you can forego having to do it with the DOM, and simply truncate the file contents like so:

    $f = fopen(&quot;document.xml&quot;, &quot;r+&quot;);
    ftruncate($f, 0);
    fclose($f);

To remove the root element in a DOMDocument, you remove the document element (the root element as I read your question) from the document similar on how to remove any other child element:

~~~
&lt;?php

$xml = &lt;&lt;&lt;XML
&lt;root/&gt;
XML;

$doc = new DOMDocument();
$doc-&gt;loadXML($xml);
$doc-&gt;save(&#39;php://output&#39;);

echo &quot;---\n&quot;;

$doc-&gt;removeChild($doc-&gt;documentElement);
$doc-&gt;save(&#39;php://output&#39;);
~~~

Output:

~~~
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt;
&lt;root/&gt;
---
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt;
~~~

(Running example: https://3v4l.org/u11Oo)

As this example shows, the document element has been removed from the document. If there would not be the XML declaration, it would be just empty.

